data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. **No Thread.Abort migration is needed.**

That said, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach would be to replace raw threads with `Task.Run` and support cancellation via `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items,
        CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item =>
            Task.Run(() => Process(item, ct), ct));

        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Thread.Sleep(100); // or await Task.Delay(100, ct)
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you cooperative cancellation (the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`) if you ever need it in the future.
